```json
{
  "global": "Decompose TDP-43's transition to pathological aggregates in stress granules via intra-condensate demixing, then predict how RRM1 stabilization and elevated saturated fatty acids alter aggregation propensity.",
  "subtasks": [
    {
      "subtask": "Establish TDP-43 structural organization and normal stress granule recruitment mechanisms",
      "atomics": [
        "Identify key TDP-43 domains: RNA recognition motifs (RRM1/RRM2), low-complexity domain (LCD), and intrinsically disordered regions",
        "Explain TDP-43's multivalent weak interactions that drive recruitment into liquid-phase condensates",
        "Characterize the initial liquidlike condensate microenvironment and functional TDP-43 population in stress granules"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Delineate TDP-43's pathological aggregation pathway with emphasis on intra-condensate demixing mechanism",
      "atomics": [
        "Describe how chronic oxidative stress triggers SG nucleation and TDP-43 partitioning into the condensate phase",
        "Explain the transition from dynamic liquidlike condensate to solid-like aggregate via secondary phase separation",
        "Analyze intra-condensate demixing: LCD undergoes spontaneous phase separation within the SG boundary, creating a denser, more dehydrated subphase",
        "Identify molecular drivers of demixing: oxidative damage (disulfide bonds, tyrosyl radicals), proteolytic cleavage, post-translational modifications, and high local concentration",
        "Explain how demixing creates hydrophobic microenvironments that accelerate β-sheet nucleation and aggregate propagation through positive feedback"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Model effects of increased RRM1 structural stability on aggregation propensity",
      "atomics": [
        "Analyze how increased RRM1 folding stability shifts the folding equilibrium toward ordered conformation, reducing conformational entropy",
        "Evaluate whether increased RRM1 stability reduces LCD exposure by constraining the LCD within a more rigid protein architecture",
        "Predict that reduced LCD accessibility decreases aggregation nucleation rate, which scales as [LCD]² for bimolecular LCD-LCD interactions",
        "Consider secondary effects on intra-condensate diffusion and demixing kinetics from increased protein rigidity"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Model effects of elevated short-chain saturated fatty acids (C6-C10) on phase behavior and aggregation",
      "atomics": [
        "Analyze how C6-C10 saturated fatty acids insert into hydrophobic patches of the LCD, reducing effective hydrophilicity",
        "Evaluate thermodynamic effects: fatty acid incorporation lowers phase-separation critical concentration and increases condensate density",
        "Predict enhanced LCD-LCD association and stronger demixing by reducing the chemical potential barrier for LCD self-association",
        "Determine how elevated fatty acids increase nucleation rate and accelerate aggregate propagation through promotion of β-sheet formation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Synthesize combined effects of RRM1 stabilization and saturated fatty acid elevation to predict net aggregation outcome",
      "atomics": [
        "Integrate opposing effects: RRM1 stabilization (↓ aggregation via reduced LCD exposure) versus fatty acid elevation (↑ aggregation via enhanced LCD self-association)",
        "Analyze mechanistic interactions: RRM1 effects primarily kinetic (nucleation rate), fatty acid effects primarily thermodynamic (phase-separation boundary)",
        "Predict net aggregation propensity: assess whether fatty acid-driven thermodynamic promotion of demixing outcompetes RRM1 kinetic protection",
        "Provide mechanistic justification: if proteolytic cleavage separates RRM1 from LCD during stress, the protective effect of RRM1 stabilization becomes moot post-cleavage, and fatty acid elevation dominates; alternatively, RRM1 stabilization may protect against protease access, partially mitigating fatty acid promotion"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "global_atomics": [
    "Verify predictions against established literature on TDP-43 biophysics, LLPS phase behavior, and ALS/FTD aggregation pathology",
    "Cross-check consistency of lipid-induced aggregation mechanisms with known effects of saturated versus unsaturated fatty acids on protein demixing and amyloidogenesis"
  ],
  "gold_actions": {
    "global": "Map TDP-43 domain structure to LLPS and demixing kinetics, compute how RRM1 stabilization alters LCD accessibility and nucleation rate, compute how C6-C10 fatty acids shift phase-separation thermodynamics and aggregate propensity, and integrate both perturbations to predict net aggregation outcome under chronic oxidative stress.",
    "subtasks": [
      {
        "subtask": "Characterize TDP-43's modular architecture: RRM1 (residues ~101–176) and RRM2 (residues ~191–262) as rigid RNA-binding domains; LCD (residues ~262–414) as the LLPS-driving sequence rich in glutamine/asparagine and weak multivalent interaction sites",
        "atomics": [
          "Map RRM1 and RRM2 as structured domains with high inherent stability; map LCD as intrinsically disordered with low sequence complexity",
          "Identify that LCD-LCD multivalent interactions drive liquid-liquid phase separation and condensate nucleation",
          "Document that post-translational modifications (phosphorylation, ubiquitination, oxidative damage) and proteolytic cleavage destabilize RRM-LCD interface, exposing LCD"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Decompose aggregation pathway: initial LLPS (liquidlike condensate formation) → intra-condensate LCD demixing (second-order phase separation) → nucleation and β-sheet propagation in demixed subphase",
        "atomics": [
          "Establish that chronic oxidative stress triggers SG assembly; TDP-43 with accessible LCD partitions into the liquidlike condensate with partition coefficient Kp >> 1",
          "Compute that within the condensate, LCD concentration rises to ~50–200 mM; at this concentration, LCD undergoes spontaneous demixing via condensation of LCD-rich oligomers",
          "Calculate that demixing produces a denser subphase (protein volume fraction φ >> 0.1) with reduced hydration shell; reduced solvation lowers the free energy for β-sheet formation",
          "Demonstrate that oxidative damage (e.g., disulfide cross-links between LCD molecules, calpain cleavage at LCD-flanking sites) accelerates demixing via positive feedback (aggregation-prone products feed back into demixing)"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Quantify RRM1 stabilization effect: compute that increased RRM1 ΔGfold → negative (more stable) reduces effective [LCD]free and decreases nucleation rate by factor of α ∝ ([LCD]WT / [LCD]variant)²",
        "atomics": [
          "Model that RRM1 stabilization reduces the Boltzmann probability of LCD unfolding and exposure; effective free LCD concentration scales as exp(−ΔΔGfold / RT)",
          "Compute that nucleation rate Jnuc ∝ [LCD]² exp(−γ⁴m² / (kT)³ρ²); reduction in [LCD] by factor of 2–5 (depending on stabilization magnitude) reduces Jnuc by factor of 4–25",
          "Conclude that RRM1 stabilization delays nucleation and reduces the steady-state aggregate mass within the condensate, yielding net ↓ aggregation propensity"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Quantify C6-C10 saturated fatty acid effect: compute that fatty acids lower critical concentration for demixing (c*_demix) and increase demixing rate by reducing surface tension and Gibbs free energy barrier",
        "atomics": [
          "Model that short-chain saturated fatty acids (hexanoate through decanoate) have interfacial free energy γ_fa ≈ 30–50 mN/m; insertion into LCD reduces effective γ_protein-solvent and lowers c*_demix by factor of ~2–3",
          "Compute that elevated [C6-C10] at 5-fold concentration increases the rate of LCD-LCD encounter and oligomerization; demixing occurs faster and at lower bulk LCD concentration",
          "Predict that fatty acids promote nucleation and aggregate growth, yielding net ↑ aggregation propensity by ~3–10 fold (depending on mechanism: thermodynamic vs. kinetic enhancement)"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Integrate RRM1 stabilization (↓ aggregation, magnitude ~2–10 fold suppression) and C6-C10 elevation (↑ aggregation, magnitude ~3–10 fold promotion) to predict combined net effect and mechanistic outcome",
        "atomics": [
          "Assess that RRM1 stabilization primarily suppresses nucleation rate (kinetic effect), while C6-C10 elevation primarily enhances demixing thermodynamics (thermodynamic effect); effects are mechanistically distinct but convergent on LCD concentration and phase behavior",
          "Model worst-case (for RRM1 protective effect): if proteolytic cleavage during oxidative stress removes RRM1 from LCD (producing free LCD C-terminal fragment), the protective effect of RRM1 stabilization is negated post-cleavage, and fatty acid effect dominates → net ↑ aggregation propensity vs. WT",
          "Model best-case (for RRM1 protective effect): if RRM1 stabilization prevents initial unfolding and protease recognition sites remain inaccessible, proteolysis is delayed and RRM1 protection persists → net effect ~neutral or slightly ↑ aggregation (fatty acid effect partially offset by RRM1 protection) relative to WT",
          "Predict most likely outcome: net ↑ aggregation propensity in the variant (RRM1-stable + C6-C10 elevated) compared to WT, because fatty acid thermodynamic effects override partial RRM1 kinetic protection; mechanistic justification is that phase-separation thermodynamics dominate aggregation under sustained high LCD concentration regimes characteristic of chronic neuroinflammation"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "global_atomics": [
      "Validate that predictions are consistent with known saturated lipid effects on protein misfolding (e.g., palmitate and oleate enhance amyloid-β and α-synuclein aggregation), and that RRM domain stabilization is protective only under conditions where proteolytic access is prevented",
      "Confirm that intra-condensate demixing is the rate-limiting step for pathological aggregation in TDP-43, and that the combined perturbations enhance demixing kinetics and thermodynamics in ways that converge on increased aggregate burden in motor neurons under chronic oxidative stress"
    ]
  }
}
```
